The paper deals with the problem of tracking and approximating data matrices in a distributed streaming model, which involves multiple sites observing distinct streams of data and communicating with a coordinator. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) sub-category. The paper also presents novel algorithms that work in a streaming fashion and incur small communication, which suggests that it could belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) sub-category. The paper deals with matrix approximation, which involves linear algebraic techniques, suggesting that it could belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category. The paper also presents experimental results with real large datasets, which suggests that it could belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) or Social and Information Networks (cs.SI) sub-categories.
